
Guide below for dealing with LetsEncrypt SSL certificate renewal.

```bash
sudo certbot certonly --standalone
Saving debug log to /var/log/letsencrypt/letsencrypt.log
Please enter the domain name(s) you would like on your certificate (comma and/or
space separated) (Enter 'c' to cancel): lb.redgold.io
Certificate not yet due for renewal

You have an existing certificate that has exactly the same domains or certificate name you requested and isn't close to expiry.
(ref: /etc/letsencrypt/renewal/lb.redgold.io.conf)

What would you like to do?
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
1: Keep the existing certificate for now
2: Renew & replace the certificate (may be subject to CA rate limits)
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
Select the appropriate number [1-2] then [enter] (press 'c' to cancel): 2
Renewing an existing certificate for lb.redgold.io

Successfully received certificate.
Certificate is saved at: /etc/letsencrypt/live/lb.redgold.io/fullchain.pem
Key is saved at:         /etc/letsencrypt/live/lb.redgold.io/privkey.pem
This certificate expires on 2023-12-25.
These files will be updated when the certificate renews.
Certbot has set up a scheduled task to automatically renew this certificate in the background.

- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
If you like Certbot, please consider supporting our work by:
 * Donating to ISRG / Let's Encrypt:   https://letsencrypt.org/donate
 * Donating to EFF:                    https://eff.org/donate-le
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
```

```
cp /etc/letsencrypt/live/lb.redgold.io/fullchain.pem ~/.rg/all/certificate.crt
```

```
cp /etc/letsencrypt/live/lb.redgold.io/privkey.pem ~/.rg/all/private_key.key`
```